  "response": "Yes, muscle growth is still possible after the age of 35. While it may become more challenging due to natural age-related changes, such as decreased testosterone and slower metabolism, individuals can still build and maintain muscle mass through:\n\n1. Resistance training\n- Weight lifting\n- Bodyweight exercises\n- Progressive overload techniques\n\n2. Proper nutrition\n- Higher protein intake\n- Balanced diet with adequate calories\n- Proper macronutrient distribution\n\n3. Hormonal considerations\n- Strength training can help boost testosterone\n- Potential hormone replacement therapy (consult a doctor)\n\n4. Recovery and rest\n- Adequate sleep\n- Proper recovery between workouts\n- Reduced risk of injury\n\n5. Supplementation\n- Protein supplements\n- Creatine\n- Vitamin D\n\nKey factors affecting muscle growth after 35:\n- Individual genetics\n- Overall health\n- Consistency in training\n- Nutrition\n- Hormone levels\n\nWhile muscle growth might be slower compared to younger years, it is absolutely achievable with the right approach to exercise, nutrition, and lifestyle.\n\nAlways consult a healthcare professional or fitness expert before starting a new exercise program, especially after 35.",
